First, draw a sketch. We can label the \(K\) axis by adding integer multiples of 18 to 79. We know to shade the left because low values of \(K\) satisfy the condition \(K<k\) (regardless of the exact value of \(k\)). We donâ€™t know exactly where to place the boundary, but we know the left area is 0.19.

It is helpful to know the following approximations:

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-3 0.001
-2 0.023
-1 0.159
0 0.5
1 0.841
2 0.977
3 0.999

So, we know the \(z\)-score is between -1 and 0. Remember, \(Z\) and \(z\) always refer to the standard normal variable.


By using the \(z\) table we can determine \(z\) more precisely.

\(z\) \(P(Z<z)\)
-0.9 0.1841
-0.89 0.1867
-0.88 0.1894
-0.87 0.1922
-0.86 0.1949
-0.89 0.1977

Either -0.88 or -0.87 is a good estimation of \(z\), and either value will lead you to an acceptable answer. Using other tools, a more accurate value can be found. I will show the work with a more accurate value. \[z=-0.8779\]

We now convert the \(z\) score into a \(k\) score. \[\begin{aligned} k &= \mu+z\sigma \\ &= 79+(-0.8779)(18) \\ &= 63.2 \end{aligned}\]

We can also visualize this with a spinner.


The tolerance for an acceptable answer was \(\pm 1\) from 63.1978667. So, anything between 62.1978667 and 64.1978667 was accepted.
